PREFACE.

Tms edition is a careful revision of the one publishedin 1882. ’

The text, as in the former edition, follows Ribbeck in the main, adhering, however, to the received ‘reading where he seems to be not fully supported by his own apparatus

The illustrations have been much increased in number and improved in execution. Many of the new ones have been inserted in the text instead of in the notes in order to present them more directly to the eye of the student when he is reading the passages that they illustrate. The pictures are intended to represent only objects or conceptions which were familiar to the minds of the poet and his contemporass ries, and consequently nothing modern has been admitted among them. For the sake of the associations, however, a number of views of the scenes in which the action takes place have been included.

The introduction deals more fully than that of the former

edition with the lise and times of Virgil, as well as with his literary models. There have been added also an entirely
